{[%evp 0,31,22,22,24,4,40,16,64,51,51,34,37,12,67,55,73,26,37,37,38,45,26,50,
57,61,64,55,67,55,47,51,56,46]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5.
h4 Bg7 6. h5 {The top choice. I find this aggressive move most consistent,} ({
although} 6. e4 Nxc3 7. dxc3 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 {leads to a comfortable endgame,
where Black has to struggle for equality.}) 6... O-O {This somewhat
provocative move was seen in no less than 13 games! Black shows his confidence
to withstand the upcoming attack along the h-file.} (6... c5 {is covered with
5...c5}) (6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 {transposes to 5...Nxc3}) (6... e5 {was seen in
Melkumyan,H - Hakobyan,E Jermuk 2022 Here I like} 7. d4 $146 exd4 (7... Nxc3 8.
bxc3 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6.}) 8. Bg5 $1 {An important intermediate move.
White either gains a tempo or provokes the weakening ...f7-f6.} Nxc3 ({Worse is
} 8... f6 $2 9. Qxd4 Nxc3 10. Qxc3 {offers White nearly a decisive positional
advantage as Black is undeveloped, and the k-side is too exposed.}) ({After} 
8... Qd6 9. h6 Be5 {White has few attractive otpions, such as} 10. Nxe5 Qxe5
11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Bf6 $14 {, regaining the pawn in a favorable situation, when
Black is missing his dark-squared bishop.}) 9. bxc3 f6 10. Bc1 $1 {The bishop
did its job, and it comes back not to interrupt White's piece coordination.}
dxc3 11. Qb3 $1 {A powerful resource. White has a few dangerous ideas, such as
..hxg6, followed by the rook's trade and Qg8+.} g5 (11... Qe7 12. e3 c5 13. Bc4
{also provides White a powerful initiative.}) 12. e3 Nc6 13. Bb5 f5 14. Ba3 $36
{Black's king is stuck in the centre, while all White's forces are getting
mobilized.}) ({The somewhat artificial} 6... Nb6 7. d4 Bg4 (7... Nc6 {
transposes to 6...Nc6.}) 8. h6 Bf6 {took place in Both, G - Gorshkova, I San
Sebastian 2011 Now the simple} 9. e3 $146 O-O 10. Be2 N8d7 11. Ne4 Bh8 12. Bd2
{offers White a stable advantage due to his superiority in the centre. For
instance,} e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Bc3 $14 {This endgame feels unpleasant for
Black because of the strong h6 pawn and the poor b6 knight.}) 7. e4 ({The more
straightforward way is} 7. hxg6 hxg6 8. Qa4 e6 9. Qg4 {, but after} e5 10. Qg3
Re8 {Black seems to have definite counterchances because White is missing his
developed pieces. Yuffa, D - Papenin, N Sochi 2016}) 7... Nxc3 8. dxc3 {White
liquidates into a nice endgame, when the Bg7 is out of play, and White has the
upper hand on the kingside.} Qxd1+ {The most natural choice, although the
queen's trade doesn't interrupt White's plans.} ({After} 8... Bg4 9. hxg6 Qxd1+
10. Kxd1 hxg6 11. Kc2 Nd7 12. Ng5 Nc5 13. Be3 $16 {Black faced problems with
his minor pieces when the g8 king is unsecured. So,W - Chirila,I Chess.com
INT 2017}) 9. Kxd1 Nd7 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Kc2 {There are some other decent
options, but White's king should be placed on c2 in all cases.} Ne5 {Black is
reasonably aiming to simplify matters.} ({Too passive is} 11... Nc5 12. Ng5 Ne6
13. Bc4 Nxg5 14. Bxg5 $16 {Harika,D - Chu,R China 2018}) 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Bc4
{A well-timed move. From now Black struggles to activate the light-squared
bishop.} Bd7 {This was Fressinet, L - Kulaots, K Germany 2019 Now I suggest} 14.
a4 $146 {preventing ...Ba4 and seizing space on the queen-side.} Bc6 (14... a5
15. Bg5 Rfe8 16. f3 $14 {is equally unpleasant.}) 15. f3 a6 16. a5 $14 {
Black lacks any constructive ideas. It will be a long-term suffering for him
whereas White can try slowly to make progress on both flanks.} *

