{[%evp 0,31,24,26,26,4,39,16,65,62,59,30,23,39,49,20,9,-58,-73,-56,-51,-48,-45,
-45,-44,-35,-32,-84,-39,-83,50,-105,-63,-53]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4.
cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 Bg7 6. h5 Nc6 7. d4 Bf5 {This logical continuation took place
in 5 games, which were all played by grandmasters. The main idea is to prevent
...e2-e4. Also, White has to watch for ...Nd5-b4 in some cases.} ({Another
ambitious response is} 7... Bg4 {By attacking the h5 pawn, Black invites White
to show his cards.} 8. h6 ({White achieves less with} 8. hxg6 hxg6 9. Rxh8+
Bxh8 10. e4 Nb6 {and it is questionable if White can benefit from the opening
of the h-file.}) 8... Bf6 9. e3 {A simple development.} ({The more aggressive} 
9. e4 {weakens d4, and after} Ndb4 $1 10. d5 Nd4 11. Bd3 c6 {Black was fine in
Naiditsch, A - Volokitin, A San Sebastian 2012}) 9... O-O 10. Be2 e5 $5 $146 {
I find this innovation very challenging - Black is aiming to convert his
slight development advantage into something concrete.} ({Too slow is} 10... Nb6
11. O-O Qc8 12. d5 Rd8 13. e4 {White has a clear advantage due to his
superiority in the centre. Georgiev,K - Kanmazalp,O Rhodes 2013}) (10... Nxc3
11. bxc3 Na5 {1/2 (26) Nepomniachtchi,I (2718)-Rodshtein,M (2641) Rogaska
Slatina 2011} 12. O-O $146 c5 13. Ba3 b6 (13... cxd4 14. cxd4 Rc8 15. Qa4 $14)
14. dxc5 Qc7 15. Qa4 Bd7 16. Bb5 $14) 11. Nxe5 Bxe2 12. Nxc6 $1 {White
liquidates into a comfortable endgame.} Bxd1 13. Nxd8 Raxd8 14. Kxd1 c5 {
of course, Black should fast energetically to obtain any compensation.} 15. Bd2
{Giving the pawn back, but neutralizing Black's initiative on the d-file.} cxd4
16. Nxd5 Rxd5 17. e4 Rd7 (17... Re5 18. f3 Rd8 19. Rc1 $14) 18. f4 {White has
to extend on the k-side.} Be7 19. g4 f6 20. Rc1 $14 {White has control over
the c-file, and Black's passer might become a weakness in the long run.}) 8.
Rh4 $1 {An original idea! White insists on .. e2-e4, although it is connected
with an exchange sacrifice.} Bf6 {Black accepts the challenge. There is hardly
an equal alternative.} ({For instance, after} 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 e5 10. e4 Bd7
11. d5 $16 {Black is too cramped.}) 9. g4 $1 {It turns out, that White has
another attractive idea at his disposal.} ({At the same time, after} 9. e4 Nxc3
10. bxc3 Bxh4 11. exf5 Bf6 {Black is doing OK.}) 9... Bxh4 10. gxf5 e6 $1 $146
{This innovation is definitely the most challenging response.} ({Worse is} 
10... Bf6 11. e4 Nxc3 12. bxc3 gxf5 ({After} 12... Rg8 13. e5 $1 Bh8 14. fxg6
hxg6 15. h6 $16 {Black is nominally an exchange up, but the position is
horrible - the Bh8 is completely out of play, and the king wouldn't be safe
anytime soon.}) 13. e5 Bg7 ({Or} 13... Bxe5 14. dxe5 $16 {Giri,A - Svidler,P
chess24.com INT 2020}) 14. h6 Bf8 15. d5 {Black will have to give up his
knight as} Nb8 $2 16. Ng5 {, followed by e5-e6 is crushing. This funny
position is a perfect illustration of White's domination - all Black's pieces
are at their initial spots!}) 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Bh3 $1 {White doesn't hesitate
to start putting pressure on Black's main weakness.} ({Instead, the ambitious} 
12. e4 Nb6 13. Be3 O-O 14. hxg6 hxg6 {leads to a double-edged play as Black
gets plenty of play along the f-file.}) 12... Qe7 ({The attempt to unbalance
the situation with} 12... Rf8 13. Qd3 Rxf3 {doesn't really work:} 14. exf3 Qd6
15. Qe4 $14 {The vulnerablity of PP g6 and e6 prevails.}) 13. Nxd5 {This
decision might be the product of confusion, but clearing the h3-c8 diagonal
White wants to prevent ...0-0-0.} exd5 14. Bh6 $1 {Now Black's king is stuck
in the centre!} Kf7 ({Black fails to release the pressure by means of} 14...
gxh5 15. Qb3 Qb4+ {, as the endgame that arises after} 16. Qxb4 Nxb4 17. Rc1
Bd8 18. a3 Nc6 19. Be6 $36 {is very unpleasant: White's bishops dominate all
over the board.}) 15. Qd2 Rae8 16. O-O-O $44 {White has interesting
compensation for the exchange - Black's king is in permanent danger, and his
rooks have no access to open files. At the same time, White has few targets
for an attack.} *

