{[%evp 0,33,39,23,19,5,32,21,59,45,41,41,41,20,12,15,23,23,35,19,55,36,19,14,
15,13,14,14,14,14,19,17,34,47,55,55]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5
Nxd5 5. h4 Bg7 6. h5 Nc6 7. d4 Nxc3 (7... Nb6 {A standard Grunfeld approach:
Black attacks the white d4 pawn in order to provoke e2-e3 which will limit
White's active possibilities.} 8. d5 {A brave decision! White sacrifices a
pawn, but it will cost Black the exchange of his strong dark-squared bishop.} (
{Instead,} 8. e3 O-O 9. hxg6 hxg6 {puts Black's king in danger, but it isn't
so easy for White to join his pieces in the attack.}) 8... Bxc3+ ({Too passive
is} 8... Ne5 9. Nxe5 Bxe5 10. e4 e6 11. a4 $1 {This move often poses concrete
problems for Black as 11...a5 weakens b5 and runs into Bb5+.} exd5 12. a5 Nd7
13. Nxd5 $36 {It is only a matter of time before White will start his
expansion with f2-f4 and e4-e5. On the other hand, Black struggles to create
any counterplay.}) 9. bxc3 Qxd5 {Of course, by trading queens Black can partly
release the tension.} 10. Qxd5 Nxd5 11. hxg6 fxg6 12. Bh6 $1 {Eliminating ...
h7-h5, so the Ph7 is a cause of worry for Black.} Rg8 ({In case of} 12... Nf6
13. e3 Bf5 14. Bc4 O-O-O 15. Bg7 Rhe8 16. Bf7 $14 {Black will not obtain
sufficient compensation for the exchange.}) 13. e4 Nb6 $146 {The most solid
choice.} ({Instead, the ''greedy''} 13... Nxc3 $6 14. Bc4 e6 15. Ng5 $16 {
put Black on the verge of collapse in Gordievsky, D - Nasuta, G Budva 2013}) 14.
a4 $1 {A decent way of maintaining the initiative. Black should either allow
a4-a5 or block the pawn with Nc6-a5.} Na5 ({After} 14... Be6 15. a5 Nd7 16. Ng5
Bf7 17. a6 $16 {Black desperately lacks harmony. In particular, the obvious 17.
.. b6? 18.Bb5 leads to fatal consequences.}) (14... a5 $2 15. Bf4 {is just bad
as Black loses a pawn and significantly weakens his q-side.}) 15. Bf4 h5 {
Black cannot afford to lose the h-pawn.} 16. Bxc7 Bd7 {Both sides mobilize
their forces. Black's main idea is 17...Rc8 with counter-play against c3.} 17.
Bxb6 {A well-timed exchange. White creates a few more targets on the
queenside.} axb6 18. Ne5 Rc8 19. Nxd7 Kxd7 20. Rh3 $14 {the bishop is
superior to Black's knight, and the vulnerability of the g6 and b6 pawns
prevails. Black is doomed to passive defence.}) 8. bxc3 e5 {This position
occurred in Gukesh, D - Mikhalevski, V La Roda 2022 Now I mostly like} 9. Bg5 $146
{White develops with a gain of tempo and interrupts Black's plans.} Qd6 (9...
f6 {is quite committing} 10. Be3 Be6 {Black covers the key a2-g8 diagonal.} 11.
Qc2 f5 12. Bg5 $1 {Again, this move is annoying. In view of ..h5-h6 Black is
forced to exchange the fianchettoed bishop.} Bf6 13. Qb2 $1 {A great tactical
resource. The White b2 queen is doing a great job by covering d4 and attacking
b7.} Rb8 (13... Bxg5 14. Nxg5 Qxg5 15. Qxb7 Kd7 16. dxe5 {with Rd1 to follow
is crushing.}) 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. e3 g5 16. O-O-O $36 {The strong pawn centre
and superior piece coordination offers White a stable advantage.}) ({In the
event of} 9... Bf6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 {at the very least White can liquidate into a
comfortable endgame with} 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Qd4 Qxd4 14. cxd4 $14
{Superiority in the centre allows White to play for a win without taking too
much risk.}) 10. h6 Bf6 11. dxe5 {The most forcing.} (11. d5 $5 Ne7 12. e4 {
also deserves serious attention.}) 11... Qxd1+ (11... Bxe5 12. Qxd6 Bxd6 13.
Bf6) 12. Rxd1 Bxg5 13. Nxg5 Nxe5 14. Rh4 $1 O-O 15. Re4 {The activity of the
white rooks puts Black in an unpleasant situation. The following line is quite
illustrative:} f6 $2 16. Rxe5 $1 fxe5 17. e4 $18 {Black is unable to prevent ..
Bc4+ and this will lead to fatal consequences. Of course, White's strong h6
pawn plays a key role in this position.} *

