{[%evp 0,29,39,23,29,5,32,21,59,41,44,37,39,39,73,65,67,66,37,28,47,10,-7,-7,0,
0,0,0,0,0,0,0]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 Nxc3 6. bxc3
h6 {The main point of this move is that ..h4-h5 will be met with g6-g5. On the
downside, it makes the whole black king-side setup less stable.} (6... h5 {
Black radically prevents h4-h5, but the weakening of the g5 square provides
White with additional resources.} 7. e4 Bg7 8. Be2 {I like this flexible
developing move - White will choose a proper moment for . .d2-d4.} c5 9. O-O
Nc6 10. Rb1 $1 {A decent move. In comparison to the main line Grunfeld with 8.
Rb1, White plays in the same way, keeping an eye on the black b7 pawn and also
removing his rook from the long diagonal keeping him out of the range of the g7
Black bishop.} O-O {This can be hardly delayed.} (10... b6 {, as in Lu,M -
Atanasov, A Chesterfield 2020 runs into} 11. d4 $146 cxd4 12. Bb5 Bd7 13. cxd4
O-O 14. Bg5 $36 {The mobile pawn centre and active piece play provide White
with a powerful initiative.}) 11. Ng5 $1 {It becomes obvious, that it is White
who clearly benefits from the inclusion of the h4 and h5 pawn moves from both
sides.} Qd6 12. f4 f6 13. Bc4+ e6 {This position was reached in Fiorito, F -
Paveto,K Villa Martelli 2021. White has many promising ways to continue, but
the most energetic is:} 14. e5 $1 fxe5 15. f5 gxf5 16. Qxh5 Rf6 17. d4 {
with a crushing attack.}) (6... c5 {doesn't have an independent value as after}
7. h5 {Black has nothing better than} Bg7 {with a transposition to another
chapter.}) 7. e4 Bg7 8. d4 {We have a key Grunfeld position with h-pawn moves
for both sides. As tournament practice has proved, this detail is beneficial
to White because Black's king will be in danger in many cases.} c5 9. Be2 {
I like this simple choice. In comparison to the Grunfeld opening, this way of
development is much more effective because the direct attack on the white d4
pawn doesn't work for Black in this position due to the weakening pawn move...
h7-h6.} Nc6 ({The alternative} 9... O-O 10. O-O Bg4 11. Rb1 $1 {allows White
to comfortably complete his development and maintain all the merits of his
setup. For instance,} b6 (11... Qc7 12. d5 Nd7 13. c4 $36) 12. Bf4 cxd4 13.
cxd4 Nc6 14. d5 {This thematic advance comes with a tempo.} Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nd4
16. e5 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 $16 {The strong d5 and e5 white pawns and the poor black
g7 bishop, make Black's position very cramped and unpleasant. Hannum, W -
Pisani,C ICCF email 2020}) ({Also after} 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Nc6 11. Be3 Bg4 12.
d5 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Ne5 14. f4 {Black was positionally busted because of the
squeezing pawn thrust ..e4-e5. Krassel,T - Texe,E Reykjavik 2023}) 10. d5 $1 {
The exchange sacrifice is especially attractive in this position.} Bxc3+ {
The only challenging response.} ({In case of} 10... Ne5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Qd2
e6 13. f4 Bg7 14. d6 $16 {White's central pawns are too strong.}) 11. Bd2 Bxa1
({After} 11... Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Na5 13. Ne5 $16 {White dominates all the board.})
12. Qxa1 Nd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Qxd4 f6 15. O-O $36 {In the classical Grunfeld
White's play for the exchange is only sufficient for equality. In this
specific position, however, Black's king is much more exposed due to the
weakening pawn move ..h7-h6. Mendonca, L - Asif, M Dhaka 2022.} *

