{[%evp 0,29,26,23,26,11,39,16,59,51,51,41,41,41,53,32,59,56,59,34,77,58,58,28,
40,36,35,22,17,0,0,2]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 Nxc3 6.
bxc3 Bg7 7. h5 O-O {was tried twice by GM Vladislav Artemiev, but it is too
provocative: the h-file can be opened at any moment, and White is able to join
his pieces in the attack:} (7... e5 {is too risky as White can prevent ...0-0
with} 8. Ba3 Nc6 9. e3 a6 10. Rb1 b6 11. d4 $36 {White has both a strong pawn
centre and the initiative on the king side. Markelova,L - Gorozhanin,M Nizhnij
Novgorod 2010}) (7... Nd7 {is too passive: this way of development limits
Black's counter-attacking abilities makes White's pawn centre much more
stable.} 8. e4 e5 {This position occurred in Eljanov, P - Turov, M Kharkov 2001
Now the simple} 9. d4 $146 exd4 10. cxd4 Nb6 11. Bg5 $36 {would have put Black
in a difficult situation due to White's strong pawn centre and superior
development.}) ({The artificial} 7... Qd5 {took place in Barbero, G - Zysk, R
Budapest 1988 White has many attractive options at his disposal, when I mostly
like:} 8. Qc2 $5 $146 {with the clear intention to push e2-e4 with the gain of
a tempo.} Bf5 9. d3 Bg4 10. h6 {A standard approach in this line: White
sometimes converts his initiative on the h-file by seizing a lot of space with
h5-h6.} Bf6 11. d4 Bf5 12. Qb3 Qxb3 13. axb3 $36 {White has a superior pawn
structure, and the potential .. e2-e4-e5 advance might challenge the awkward
f6 bishop.}) (7... Bg4 {This move weakens b7, while the idea of ...Bxf3 is
dubious as Black concesses his strong bishop and doesn't really create
weaknesses in the opponent's camp.} 8. Qb3 Bxf3 9. exf3 b6 {This was Bartholomew,J
- Danelia,M Dallas 2015 White should have played} 10. d4 $146 O-O 11. Bd3 $40 {
Black's king is very exposed as Black is missing pieces on the king-side.}) (
7... Nc6 {Traditionally diminishes Black's control of d4 as ...c7-c5 is
impossible.} 8. e4 {White starts to build a strong pawn centre.} (8. d4 $5 {
also scores well in practice.}) 8... O-O (8... e5 9. Ba3 Bg4 10. Qb3 $16 {
was highly unpleasant for Black, who's king is stuck in the centre and b7 is
hanging. Yuffa, D - Praggnanandhaa, R Pardubice 2016}) 9. d4 b6 {This was
Siebrecht, S - Holtel, J Magdeburg 2020 Here I suggest the most straightforward}
10. hxg6 $146 hxg6 11. Ng5 $40 {with 12.Qf3 to follow. Black struggles to
secure his king.}) 8. hxg6 hxg6 9. Ba3 {A multi-tasking move: White not only
pins the e7 pawn, but also prevents ...c7-c5.} ({Pointless is} 9. Qa4 $6 e5
$132 {, and the queen is not getting on h4.}) 9... Re8 10. e4 $1 e5 {I find
this move the most challenging for White - the fixed pawn centre provides
Black with more chances to withstand the upcoming white attack.} (10... Nd7 $6
{was played in Carlsen, M - Artemiev, V chess24.com INT 2020 Now the
straightforward} 11. Ng5 $1 $146 e6 12. Qg4 c5 13. Qh4 $40 {puts Black's king
in grave danger.}) 11. Bc5 $1 {A great idea. The a3 bishop did his job, so
White transfers him on e3, where he will support the potential ..d3-d4 pawn
advance and will keep an eye on the important squares along the c1-h6 diagonal.
} Nc6 12. Be3 Bg4 13. Be2 Qd7 {Both sides have almost mobilized their forces.
White's king is still in the centre, but he is hardly in a bigger danger than
the g8 black king.} 14. g3 Rad8 15. Kf1 $14 {White will next play 16.Kg2 in
order to connect his heavy pieces. It feels like Black struggles to develop
any counter-play on the queen-side, while his g8 king is under long-term
pressure in view of the threats on the h-file.} *

