{[%evp 0,37,23,23,26,11,39,16,59,67,45,41,46,54,43,27,66,46,88,29,22,18,10,-1,
-1,0,6,12,13,-8,6,18,8,8,8,-18,-18,-18,-18,-32]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. h5 c5 {The most common and flexible
continuation. Black makes it tougher for White to occupy the centre with d2-d4
and leaves his king in the centre for a while.} 8. Qa4+ $1 {A tricky idea -
Black has many ways to cover his king from check, but they will all interrupt
his natural development.} Nd7 {For some reason, this natural move was only
seen in 2 games so far. Black is aiming for another fianchetto, that will be
possible after ...a7-a6 and b7-b6/b5.} (8... Nc6 {is the most active, but
leaves the c5 pawn much more vulnerable.} 9. Ba3 Qd6 {This feels very
uncomfortable as Black pins the c5 pawn.} ({After} 9... Qb6 10. Ng5 $1 Bd7 11.
Qc4 {White wins a pawn because of double attack.}) 10. d4 Bd7 ({After} 10... b6
$6 11. h6 Bf6 12. e4 Bd7 13. Bb5 $18 {Black suffered heavy material losses in
view of 14.e5. Navara, D - Djukic,N Terme Catez 2021}) 11. Qc4 b6 12. h6 $1 {
Black is provoked to place his bishop on f6, where it always invites ..e4-e5.}
Bf6 13. e4 e5 14. dxc5 $16 {White was just up a pawn in Santos Latasa,J -
Roseneck,J Tegernsee 2021}) (8... Bd7 {was seen in Wojtaszek, R - Mikhalevski,
V Terme Catez 2021 Here my new idea is} 9. Qc4 $5 $146 b6 {The most natural
reaction, although Black will suffer from the weak light squares on the
queenside.} ({After} 9... Na6 10. e4 b5 11. Qe2 O-O 12. hxg6 hxg6 13. Qe3 $36
{White has decent attacking prospects, and the black a6 knight is out of play.}
) (9... Qc7 {meets} 10. Ng5 $1 e6 11. Rb1 Na6 12. Qh4 {, and then Black has
nothing better than entering an unbalanced position with} h6 13. hxg6 hxg5 14.
Qxh8+ Bxh8 15. Rxh8+ Ke7 16. Rxa8 $14 {The rooks overwhelm Black's queen.}) 10.
Qf4 {The queen has done her job by provoking b7-b6. Now she can take part in
attacking actions.} Nc6 11. Ng5 $1 {White keeps playing aggressively.} f6 ({
Hardly better is} 11... Ne5 12. hxg6 hxg6 13. Rxh8+ Bxh8 14. d4 $16) 12. hxg6
Ne5 {The lesser evil.} ({In the event of} 12... hxg6 13. Rxh8+ Bxh8 14. Qc4 Bf5
15. Ne6 Bxe6 16. Qxe6 $16 {White has a huge positional advantage due to full
control over light squares.}) 13. Nf7 Nxf7 14. gxf7+ Kxf7 15. e4 $36 {Black
has no proper compensation for his ruined king-side.}) (8... Qd7 9. Qc4 {
White gains an important tempo by attacking c5.} b6 10. Ng5 {The most
energetic. The fianchetto is rarely well combined with ...e7-e6.} e6 ({In case
of} 10... Qf5 11. d4 Ba6 12. Qb3 $16 {the Qf5 is certainly misplaced, and
e2-e4 is on the way.}) 11. Qh4 $1 {A perfect spot for White's queen. From now
the vulnerability of dark squares starts to tell.} Qe7 (11... Nc6 {can be well
met by} 12. Ne4 Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Kxe7 14. h6 Bf8 15. d4 $36 {The threat of 16.
Bg5+ is very annoying. Rallabandi,P - Weber,J ICCF email 2020}) 12. hxg6 {
White goes for an attractive queen sacrifice to maintain his initiative.} hxg6
13. Qxh8+ Bxh8 14. Rxh8+ Kd7 15. d4 (15. f4 $5 {is worth attention, and then
16.Rh7 is to follow.}) 15... Nc6 16. Rh7 Nd8 {Black managed to avoid the loss
of material, but it costs him placing his pieces awkwardly.} 17. Ne4 {Now g5
is vacant for the bishop.} Bb7 18. Bg5 Qf8 19. Nf6+ Kc8 20. e4 $36 {The
powerful pawn centre and full control over dark squares provide White with more
than sufficient compensation for the material deficit. Rallabandi, P -
Rawlings, A ICCF email 2021}) 9. g3 $146 {I like this new move: the
fianchettoed bishop will be especially strong when Black's bishop is blocked.
Also, White keeps h4 vacant for his queen.} ({Instead,} 9. e4 {seems less
promising as White blocks the 4th rank for his queen. For instance,} Qc7 10.
Rb1 O-O 11. hxg6 hxg6 {was unclear in Shulman, Y - Palus, R Port Erin 2002}) 9...
b6 ({The consistent} 9... a6 {is calmly met by} 10. Bg2 {and it turns out that
Black still struggles to comfortably develop his queen-side pieces. For
instance:} Qc7 ({The alternatives are:} 10... Rb8 11. d4 b5 12. Qc2 Bb7 13. h6
Bf6 14. e4 cxd4 15. cxd4 $36 {White is better because of his powerful pawn
centre and his space advantage on the kingside.}) ({and} 10... b5 11. Qf4 Ra7
12. Ng5 O-O 13. Qh4 $40 {White's attacking potential is significant.}) 11. Qh4
Bf6 ({After} 11... Ne5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. a4 Rb8 14. a5 $14 {Black will be
forced to weaken his pawn chain with ...b7-b6 at some point.}) 12. Ng5 {
The most ambitious way. White doesn't fear of pin.} h6 13. hxg6 Ne5 ({Worse is
} 13... fxg6 $6 14. Ne6 Qd6 15. Qe4 $16) 14. g7 Bxg7 15. Nf3 $14 {White's pawn
structure is more healthy, and the Bg2 is very strong.}) 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. h6 $1
{White can hardly benefit from opening the h-file before Black castles.
Therefore, it is a good moment for playing this move, as Black only has f6
vacant for his bishop.} Bf6 12. O-O O-O 13. d4 {There is no reason for White
to deviate from occupying the centre.} a6 14. Qb3 b5 15. Rd1 cxd4 16. cxd4 {
Black has reached maximum progress on the queenside, but the central strategy
prevails.} Nb6 17. Nh2 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Rc8 19. Nf3 $14 {It is only a matter of
time before White will fully occupy the centre with e2-e4. There are no entry
squares for the c8 rook, so Black's counter-play is insufficient.} *

