{[%evp 0,31,23,23,26,-5,32,16,32,30,40,50,34,29,29,28,28,31,25,25,40,37,61,48,
47,47,69,35,38,18,14,35,54,36]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 {This move
often shows Black's intention to enter KID, but we will consider possible
deviations that are typical for Grunfeld players.} 4. e4 e5 5. Nxe5 Nxe4 ({
Dubious is} 5... Qe7 6. d4 d6 7. Nf3 Nxe4 {Black regains the pawn, but the
early queen's move backfires.} 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Bd3 O-O ({After} 9... f5 10. O-O
O-O 11. Re1 c6 12. Nc3 $16 {Black lacks development and the committing f7-f5
pawn move makes his setup tricky to handle.}) 10. Bxe4 Re8 11. O-O Rxe4 {
This was Eisenbeiser, A - Kessler, L Austria 2014 White should have developed
his initiative by means of} 12. Bg5 $1 $146 f6 13. Bd2 c6 14. Nc3 Re8 15. Re1
$36 {White is much better developed, and after ..d4-d5 Black will face serious
problems in covering the weak d6 pawn.}) 6. Nxe4 Bxe5 7. d4 {It is always a
pleasure to make such a move with a gain of tempo.} Bg7 8. Bg5 {The most
energetic. Black is forced to temporarily block his bishop.} f6 9. Be3 O-O ({
Worse is} 9... Qe7 $6 10. Nc3 d6 11. g3 Nc6 12. Bg2 O-O 13. O-O $16 {The Qe7
is definitely misplaced. Mchedlishvili, M - Piorun, K Warsaw 2010}) 10. g3 d6 (
10... d5 {is too risky for Black as he will have to remain with his queen in
the centre:} 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. Bg2 Qb5 {took place in Mchedlishvili, M -
Nadanian, A Tbilisi 1996 Here the most energetic was} 13. a4 $1 $146 Qxb2 14.
O-O Nc6 15. Rb1 Qa2 16. Nc5 {Black struggles to complete his development.
White has nearly a decisive advantage.}) 11. Bg2 Nc6 12. O-O f5 ({In case of} 
12... Ne7 13. Re1 Nf5 {it makes sense for White to provoke further weakening
moves from Black starting with:} 14. Bf4 g5 (14... Bd7 15. Qd3 {Black was
doomed to passive defence in Goganov, A - Zabotin, A Sochi 2017}) 15. Bc1 Nh6 16.
b4 $14 {White takes the upper hand on the queen-side, while Black's
counter-play is questionable.}) 13. Nc3 f4 {This position occurred in Bacrot, E
- Erenberg,A Chess.com INT 2022} (13... g5 14. f4 g4 15. Re1 {doesn't provide
Black with any activity on the king-side. White will soon extend with b2-b4
and d4-d5.}) {Now the simple} 14. Bxf4 $146 Nxd4 15. Re1 Bf5 16. Rc1 $14 {
offers White a stable positional advantage due to his strong g2 bishop and
control over the e-file.} *

