{[%evp 0,39,24,26,26,4,39,30,39,30,83,56,61,39,53,52,44,34,55,34,38,41,41,40,
40,23,23,23,28,31,29,46,31,29,30,45,0,18,35,24,34,38]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3.
Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 e5 5. Nxe5 O-O {This pawn sacrifice is currently Black's main
attempt to solve his problems in the 4...e5 line. The e-file is open, so
White should play accurately to complete his development.} 6. Nf3 {White moves
his knight back in advance in view of the subsequent Re8 move from Black.} Re8
({The aggressive} 6... Nxe4 7. Nxe4 Re8 8. d3 f5 9. Bg5 Bf6 {was seen in
Huzman, A - Sarkar, J Lichess.org INT 2020 White could have maintained all his
merits by means of} 10. Be2 $1 $146 fxe4 11. dxe4 Bxg5 12. Qd5+ Kg7 13. Nxg5
$16) 7. d3 {The most common and natural move.} ({The alternative} 7. Bd3 Nxe4
8. Bxe4 Bxc3 9. dxc3 Rxe4+ 10. Be3 {looks scary for Black because he is
missing his fianchetto bishop. Still, after} Nc6 11. O-O d6 12. h3 Qf6 {
White hardly has significant attacking potential. eventually, the game
Caruana,F - Mamedyarov, S Baku 2021 even ended in Black's victory.}) 7... d5 {
Of course, Black has to play very aggressively to justify the loss of the e5
pawn.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bd2 Bg4 (9... Qd6 {vacates f4 for the knight, but it
still feels artificial.} 10. Rc1 c5 11. Be2 Nf4 12. O-O {White has completed
his development.} Bg4 13. Bxf4 Qxf4 {Laan, A - Leijen, P ICCF email 2019 Here, I
mostly like the following plan:} 14. Nd2 $146 Be6 15. g3 Qd6 16. f4 $14 {
White is up a pawn, and the e4-e5 advance will neutralize the strong g7 bishop
soon.}) ({Too slow is also} 9... c5 10. Be2 Nb4 11. O-O N8c6 {, as in
Narayanan, S - Gupta, A chess24.com INT 2022 Now White should have played} 12.
Bg5 $146 Qd6 13. Nb5 Qd7 14. a3 Na6 15. Qc2 $16 {Black doesn't have
compensation for the missing pawn as his a6 knight is out of play.}) 10. Be2
Bxf3 (10... Nb4 11. Be3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 {leads to the same.}) 11. gxf3 Nb4 {
Black builds his counter-play on White's damaged pawn structure.} 12. Be3 N8c6 {
Preventing ..d3-d4 is essential for Black.} 13. a3 Na6 14. Nb5 $1 {I like this
dynamic approach: White is ready to sacrifice a pawn or even more to seize the
initiative.} (14. h4 {is another logical way but after} Nd4 15. h5 Nc5 16.
hxg6 hxg6 $44 {Black's active knights provide Black a sufficient counter-play.
Stern,R - Florstedt,J Berlin 2022}) 14... Nd4 {Black reasonably fixes control
of d4-square.} (14... Bxb2 {can be well met by} 15. d4 $1 Bxa1 16. Qxa1 Na5 {
This move is aimed at driving the Nb5 away with c7-c6.} ({Also after} 16...
Qh4 17. O-O Rad8 18. Qc1 $36 {Black's pieces are well restricted by strong
central pawns, and White's bishop pair plays an important role too.}) 17. h4 c6
18. Nc3 h5 19. f4 $36 {Black's king feels desperately weak now, as the black
knights are too far away from the action.}) 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 {We have been
following Donchenko, A - Tomczak, J Polanica Zdroj 2022 Here my new ambitious
idea is} 16. h4 $5 $146 {There is no need to spend a tempo for covering b2.}
Nc5 ({Worse is} 16... Bxb2 $6 17. Rb1 Bc3+ 18. Kf1 Bd4 19. f4 $16 {White's
king is absolutely safe, while the k-side initiative is lasting itself.}) 17.
f4 ({The straightforward} 17. h5 $5 {also comes into consideration. For
instance,} Qf6 18. hxg6 hxg6 19. Rb1 Rad8 20. Qd2 {Both kings are unsecured,
but White is a pawn up, and Black has to do with a subsequent pawn storm
starting with f2-f4, e.t.c}) 17... Qd6 ({In case of} 17... Qf6 18. Rc1 $1 Ne6 {
the Qf6 is less mobile, so White can exploit it by means of} 19. e5 Qe7 20. h5
{The Pb2 isn't so valuable!} Bxb2 21. hxg6 hxg6 22. f5 $40 {with a powerful
attack.}) 18. Qc2 {A decent consolidating move. White is getting closer to
connecting his rooks, and his pawns are covered.} Rad8 ({After} 18... Ne6 19. Qd2
Rad8 20. h5 $36 {White is up a pawn, and after ..0-0-0 Black's king will get
under attack.}) 19. Rd1 h5 20. Rg1 $36 {Black's pieces are optimally placed in
the centre, but it's hard for him to make serious threats. At the same time,
f4-f5 is in the air for White.} *

