{[%evp 0,33,32,24,22,3,32,21,46,30,31,22,38,45,34,30,30,23,29,24,24,5,9,15,30,
32,37,21,15,39,31,37,40,33,33,18]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 c5 {
This is another possible way of deviating from KID.} 5. d4 Qa5 {Gruenfeld
players often opt for this line to avoid either KID or Marocy, which emerges
after 5...cxd4.} 6. Bd3 cxd4 ({Black can also play} 6... d6 {, but after} 7.
O-O {he has hardly anything better than} cxd4 ({After} 7... Bg4 8. d5 Nbd7 9.
Be2 O-O 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 $14 {White has both the bishop pair and a big space
advantage. Schmidt,W-Garcia Martinez,S Camaguey 1974}) 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nb3 Qd8
10. Be2 O-O 11. Be3 {transposes to 6...cxd4}) 7. Nxd4 Nc6 {We have an original
version of Maroczy with White's bishop on d3 instead of e2} 8. Nb3 {Since
White has a development advantage it makes sense to keep more pieces on the
board.} Qd8 (8... Qc7 {is hardly an improvement as the queen's location isn't
optimal.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Be2 {White unblocks the d-file and eliminates ideas
such as Nc6-e5.} d6 11. Be3 b6 12. Rc1 {The opposition on the c-file is
traditionally unpleasant for Black.} Bb7 13. Qd2 Rac8 14. f3 Rfe8 15. Rfd1 $14 {
White was firmly in a control due to his big space advantage in Iturrizaga
Bonelli,E - Markowski,T Suwalki 2019}) 9. Be3 d6 10. Be2 {The d3-bishop did
its job. Now it comes back to cover g4.} O-O 11. O-O a5 {A somewhat committing
move, but Black is trying to claim some drawbacks by the placing of the
white's knight on b3.} ({The alternatives are:} 11... Be6 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Nd2 {
A sensible idea - first of all White secures the c4 pawn to neutralize any
counter-play of the opponent.} Nd7 ({Pointless is} 13... Na5 $6 14. b3 Nd7 15.
f4 $16) 14. f4 {Now it is a perfect moment to start action on the king-side.
Black has to do with the unpleasant f4-f5 threat} Bd4 15. Bxd4 Nxd4 {This
position occurred in Gajek, R - Weichhold, P Gorzow Wielkopolski 2014 White
should have continued:} 16. b3 $146 a6 17. Nf3 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 $14 {Black lacks
space, and his king is more exposed after the trade of dark-squared bishops.})
({The second fianchetto traditionally puts Black in a passive position as he
lacks any counter-attacking ideas with b6-b5 or d6-d5:} 11... b6 12. Qd2 Bb7
13. f3 Rc8 14. Nd4 Ne5 15. b3 $14 {Hansen,L - Sokolov,I Bled 1991}) 12. Rc1 a4
({After} 12... Bd7 13. Nd2 Nb4 14. f3 Bc6 15. Nb3 {Black faces a space problem.
Dorfman,J - Vasiukov,E Moscow 1989}) 13. Nd2 a3 {The only attempt to create
counterplay, although it is also a committing decision.} 14. b3 Nb4 {White's
knight is currently tied to defending a2, but it isn't for too long. We have
been following the game Pavlov, S -Kislinsky, A Dnipro 2019 Now I like the
following way to regroup the pieces:} 15. Nf3 $1 $146 Ng4 (15... Bg4 {doesn't
change much:} 16. Nd4 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 $16) 16. Bd2 Bd7 17. Ne1 $14 {with 17.Nc2
to follow. After the subsequent knight's trade, Black will find himself in an
unpleasant position, when the pawn on a3 is going to be a permanent weakness.}
*

