{[%evp 0,31,32,24,45,3,32,21,46,31,22,30,45,30,54,57,73,63,65,49,49,38,42,4,31,
31,44,42,44,40,11,7,16,17]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 c5 5. d4 Qa5
6. Bd3 Ng4 {This attempt to interrupt White's development by attacking the d4
pawn looks artificial. Still, it was played by a few strong grandmasters, such
as Ragger and Li Chao.} 7. Be2 $1 {White can afford to waste a tempo for
keeping control of d4.} Nc6 ({The more concrete approach is} 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
Qc5 {, but it can be refuted with} 9. Ncb5 $1 a6 10. Bxg4 axb5 11. Nxb5 Qxc4
12. Be2 Qc6 13. Bg5 $16 {White's development advantage is threatening. Schmidt,
J-Malewicz, F DESC email 2010}) 8. d5 {White grabs a lot of space.} (8. dxc5 $5
Qxc5 9. O-O {looks also promising.}) 8... Nd4 (8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nce5 10. Nxe5
Nxe5 11. O-O $16 {, followed by f2-f4 looks awful for Black, who is missing
his fianchettoed bishop}) 9. O-O Qc7 {Natural play by both sides led to this
position in Laznicka, V - Ragger, M Novy Bor 2017} ({In case of} 9... Nxe2+ 10.
Qxe2 d6 11. Bf4 {White is fully mobilized, and e4-e5 is soon to follow.} O-O
12. e5 dxe5 13. Nxe5 $36 {Black is very cramped, and the e7pawn is weak.
Aronian,L - Li,C Doha 2016}) 10. e5 $1 $146 {This is much more energetic than
10.g3. White takes advantage of his superior development to pose Black
concrete problems.} Nxe5 ({After} 10... Nxf3+ 11. gxf3 $1 Nxe5 12. f4 $18 {
the knight is gone.}) 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Nb5 Qb6 ({After} 12... Qd8 {White has
a few good-looking possibilities, but I mostly like} 13. f4 $1 d3 14. fxe5 dxe2
15. Qxe2 O-O 16. Bg5 {with a nearly decisive advantage.}) 13. d6 $1 {
Preventing Black from moving his light-squared bishop.} exd6 14. Nxd4 a6 ({
Black doesn't achieve much by simplification:} 14... Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Nf3+ 16.
Bxf3 Bxd4 17. Bd5 $16 {and the queen-side pieces are stuck.}) 15. Nc2 O-O 16.
Ne3 $16 {Black's extra pawn has no much value - White's knight will land on d5
and dominate Black's pieces.} *

